The paper deals with computing convolutions of private and public inputs while satisfying differential privacy, which involves techniques from data structures (such as Fourier Transforms), information theory (such as adding Laplacian noise), cryptography (such as differential privacy), machine learning (such as time series analysis), and signal processing (such as linear filtering). Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), followed by cs.IT (Information Theory), cs.CR (Cryptography and Security), cs.LG (Machine Learning), and cs.SI (Signal Processing).
